1
00:00:00,292 --> 00:00:03,918
When the call to prayer came, we prayed two rakaas [a unit of prayer]

2
00:00:04,626 --> 00:00:07,834
After the interrogation ended, we prayed two rakaas

3
00:00:08,918 --> 00:00:11,542
And after the prayer they took me down this path

4
00:00:12,125 --> 00:00:13,584
There was an opening here

5
00:00:14,375 --> 00:00:15,709
That led to the bishopric

6
00:00:17,417 --> 00:00:20,918
We went there, and stayed until they held the obligatory prayer

7
00:00:21,542 --> 00:00:23,125
We all prayed together

8
00:00:23,959 --> 00:00:28,667
After that, and after the obligatory prayer, the interrogation started

9
00:00:29,334 --> 00:00:31,500
Interviewer: When you prayed the sunnah here, were you in <i>wudu</i> [ablution]?

10
00:00:31,584 --> 00:00:32,792
Or did you tell them you wanted to do <i>wudu</i>?

11
00:00:33,292 --> 00:00:35,500
No, I was already in <i>wudu</i> since they’d taken me from my shop

12
00:00:36,209 --> 00:00:37,792
Interviewer: The prayer you did together there

13
00:00:37,792 --> 00:00:41,751
Interviewer: Was the imam one of their men or one of you?
Witness: One of their men

14
00:00:42,125 --> 00:00:43,959
Interviewer: Can you describe the prayer for me?

15
00:00:43,959 --> 00:00:46,500
Was it a normal prayer? Was there any special <i>duaa</i> [supplication]?

16
00:00:46,542 --> 00:00:50,000
No, there was no <i>duaa</i>, just a normal sunnah prayer

17
00:00:50,709 --> 00:00:52,959
Interviewer: The obligatory or the sunnah?
Witness: Sorry, the obligatory

18
00:00:54,167 --> 00:00:55,500
It was just a normal noon prayer

19
00:00:56,334 --> 00:00:58,542
Interviewer: Didn’t he make a <i>duaa</i> of qunout for example?

20
00:00:59,626 --> 00:01:00,918
No, he didn’t as far as I remember

21
00:01:01,751 --> 00:01:05,250
Interviewer: What happened after the prayer?
Witness: After the prayer we sat

22
00:01:06,500 --> 00:01:08,709
For a bit, then they took us to the interrogation

23
00:01:10,042 --> 00:01:14,542
And during the interrogation he started asking me about the medicine

24
00:01:16,167 --> 00:01:18,959
Where was the source of the medicine I was bringing

25
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:20,792
I told him it was from people who wanted good deeds

26
00:01:21,125 --> 00:01:23,918
They brought it to me and asked me to distribute it for God’s reward

27
00:01:26,042 --> 00:01:29,459
And there were women who came to me at the shop

28
00:01:30,042 --> 00:01:31,959
It turned out those women were from them

29
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:35,042
They brought me a prescription and said they were in need

30
00:01:36,334 --> 00:01:38,626
They said to me, Can you provide us with this medicine?

31
00:01:39,459 --> 00:01:40,792
They thought I was selling it

32
00:01:42,584 --> 00:01:44,209
What I had with me I gave them

33
00:01:45,083 --> 00:01:46,959
Interviewer: For money or free?
Witness: Free

34
00:01:47,292 --> 00:01:51,250
Free, even an inhaler for asthma treatment was marked for free distribution

35
00:01:52,959 --> 00:01:54,918
Tenorfin for high blood pressure was marked for free distribution

36
00:01:55,792 --> 00:01:59,500
Isordin and Angised, the tablet under the tongue for heart disease

37
00:02:00,125 --> 00:02:01,375
These were what I gave them

38
00:02:03,167 --> 00:02:05,626
I suspected them before I was detained

39
00:02:06,584 --> 00:02:07,918
It was clear they were sending them to me

40
00:02:10,417 --> 00:02:11,417
And the ones who came were women

41
00:02:12,459 --> 00:02:18,542
They wanted to see if I sold or bought or gave for free

42
00:02:18,834 --> 00:02:21,626
But I gave it for free to the poor, for the sake of God

43
00:02:22,167 --> 00:02:23,959
Interviewer: Was the person who interrogated you there

44
00:02:23,959 --> 00:02:25,209
The same one who interrogated you here?

45
00:02:25,334 --> 00:02:26,334
No, a different person

46
00:02:26,834 --> 00:02:28,959
Interviewer: How was his style and the way
he treated you during the interrogation?

47
00:02:30,542 --> 00:02:36,542
His style was harsh with me

48
00:02:37,709 --> 00:02:40,584
I mean his way of speaking was terrifying

49
00:02:41,918 --> 00:02:43,167
As if he wanted to slaughter me

50
00:02:43,709 --> 00:02:45,292
Interviewer: Did they ask you the same questions here and there?

51
00:02:45,375 --> 00:02:48,375
Yes, almost the same questions there

52
00:02:48,417 --> 00:02:49,918
Interviewer: Did he ask you for something specific there?

53
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:53,083
Like, join us or support us so we can release you?

54
00:02:53,751 --> 00:02:55,209
No, he didn’t ask me that

55
00:02:55,959 --> 00:02:57,876
He asked me, What do you think of ISIS?

56
00:02:57,959 --> 00:03:02,751
And out of fear I told him, ISIS and you are right

57
00:03:02,751 --> 00:03:04,167
And so on, just out of fear

58
00:03:05,959 --> 00:03:08,459
I told him, You are right and you are this and that

59
00:03:11,167 --> 00:03:14,375
Interviewer: When you were saying out of fear that they were right

60
00:03:14,417 --> 00:03:16,959
Witness: Yes, out of terror
Interviewer: Do you think he believed you?

61
00:03:18,292 --> 00:03:19,959
As he wished, if he believed me or not

62
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:22,667
But I knew they were criminals

63
00:03:23,417 --> 00:03:24,417
Interviewer: I understand your words

64
00:03:24,459 --> 00:03:28,209
But when you told him they were right while you were scared

65
00:03:28,250 --> 00:03:29,459
Do you think he believed you?

66
00:03:30,667 --> 00:03:32,500
No, I don’t think he believed me

67
00:03:33,167 --> 00:03:36,417
Interviewer: Did you feel that they knew they were in the wrong?

68
00:03:36,459 --> 00:03:37,584
They were wrong, that’s certain

69
00:03:37,626 --> 00:03:38,792
Interviewer: Did they know that?

70
00:03:38,792 --> 00:03:40,083
Yes, they knew they were wrong

71
00:03:41,918 --> 00:03:45,167
They were wrong, without a doubt
